1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:37,247
Walk into any store in America and ask for a pair of sunglasses. You can pick Ray-Ban, Oakley, Prada, Versace, or Persol. Eight different brands, eight different price points, and the illusion of fierce competition. ... But here is the secret they do not want you to know: every single one of those brands is owned by the exact same company. A single Italian eyewear giant controls the frames on your face, the store where you bought them, and even the insurance that paid for them. And they built this empire by turning a five-dollar piece of plastic into a four-hundred-dollar purchase.

2
00:00:37,247 --> 00:01:26,495
Our story begins in a small mountain town in northern Italy called Agordo, in the year 1961. A young man named Leonardo Del Vecchio had spent his childhood in an orphanage, learning the trade of making metal molds for car parts and eyeglass frames. ... With a loan from a local bank, he opened a small workshop with just a handful of employees. The workshop was cramped, poorly lit, and freezing in the winter. At that moment, no investor or banker saw anything special in this venture. It was just another tiny Italian manufacturing shop in a country full of them. But Del Vecchio had a vision that none of his competitors understood: he did not want to just make frames. He wanted to control every step, from the raw material to the moment a customer tried them on.

3
00:01:26,495 --> 00:02:11,304
What made Del Vecchio different was his obsession with vertical integration. While other eyewear companies designed frames in Milan and then contracted the manufacturing to separate factories across Asia, Del Vecchio built his own production line from the ground up. He purchased the most advanced machinery available, hired the best Italian craftsmen, and established a fully integrated assembly process under a single factory roof. ... By the 1970s, Luxottica was not just making frames. They were making the hinges, the screws, the temples, and even the cases. Every single component was produced by the same company, giving them absolute control over quality, cost, and most importantly, profit margins.

4
00:02:11,304 --> 00:03:03,816
By the 1990s, Luxottica had mastered manufacturing. They were making millions of frames a year, but Del Vecchio saw a problem. The big retail chains were capturing most of the profit. A frame that cost Luxottica fifteen dollars to make was being sold in stores for two hundred dollars. The retailers were making more money than the manufacturer. ... So Del Vecchio did something unprecedented. He stopped selling to the middlemen and started buying them. In a series of aggressive acquisitions, Luxottica purchased LensCrafters, Sunglass Hut, Pearle Vision, and Target Optical. Suddenly, the company that made the glasses also owned the stores where you bought them. The vertical integration was complete. The manufacturing cost stayed the same, but the retail price kept climbing.

5
00:03:03,816 --> 00:03:57,864
But owning the stores was not enough. Luxottica needed to own the brands that customers actually wanted. In 1999, they purchased Ray-Ban, the most iconic sunglasses brand in the world, for six hundred and forty million dollars. Then came Oakley, the sports eyewear giant, for two point one billion. Then Persol, Vogue, Oliver Peoples, and dozens more. ... Year after year, the headlines announced another acquisition. Year one, Ray-Ban joins the family. Year two, the global retail network expands. Year three, Oakley falls. Year four, Luxottica controls over eighty percent of the major eyewear brands on the planet. The motion graphic of their growth looks like a military campaign, with each new brand added to the empire like a conquered territory.

6
00:03:57,864 --> 00:04:47,495
As Luxottica's grip tightened, the price of eyewear began to climb far faster than inflation. By the early 2000s, the average pair of prescription glasses in the United States cost over three hundred dollars, despite research showing that the actual manufacturing cost was somewhere between two and five dollars. ... Internal memos and industry reports revealed a coordinated strategy. Without direct competitors in the premium frame market, Luxottica could set whatever price it wanted. If a retailer tried to offer discounts, Luxottica would threaten to pull their most popular brands from the shelves. The illusion of choice was complete. Consumers could walk into any store, pick any of the dozens of brands on display, and unknowingly hand their money to the same Italian corporation every single time.

7
00:04:47,495 --> 00:05:37,536
But Luxottica's most brilliant strategy was yet to come. They realized that even if they controlled the brands and the stores, customers still had one escape route: independent optometrists and insurance providers. So they bought those too. ... In 2015, Luxottica acquired EyeMed, one of the largest vision insurance providers in the United States. Think about what this means. Luxottica makes the frames, sells them in their stores, and then also decides how much your insurance will reimburse you. If you try to buy a cheaper frame from a competitor, EyeMed's policies conveniently offer better coverage for Luxottica products. It is a closed loop, a perfectly engineered system where every path leads back to the same company, regardless of the choice the customer believes they are making.

8
00:05:37,536 --> 00:06:25,824
Journalists and regulators began to connect the dots. Investigative reporters from major newspapers started digging into Luxottica's vertical monopoly, publishing exposés that revealed the true extent of the company's control over the eyewear industry. ... In the newsrooms, evidence boards filled with photographs of Luxottica offices, acquisition timelines, and family trees connecting brands. Regulatory filings were pulled from government databases. Court building exteriors appeared in the background of broadcast reports. The European Commission opened an antitrust investigation, questioning whether Luxottica's dominance violated competition laws. The world was finally waking up to the quiet empire that had been built in plain sight, one pair of glasses at a time.

9
00:06:25,824 --> 00:07:19,199
When the scrutiny intensified, Luxottica did not retreat. They went on the offensive. Their legal teams argued that the company simply offered consumers the best products at the best prices, and that their size was a result of superior quality, not anti-competitive behavior. They pointed to new competitors like Warby Parker as proof that the market was open and competitive. ... But investigators noted that Luxottica owned the supply chains, the retail real estate, and the insurance networks that new entrants would need to scale. Warby Parker could sell online, but the moment a customer walked into a physical store, they were walking into Luxottica territory. The regulatory filings piled higher. The court hearings continued. But the empire was too large, too embedded, and too politically connected to face any real consequences.

10
00:07:19,199 --> 00:08:17,615
But even the mightiest empires face disruption. In 2010, a startup called Warby Parker entered the market with a radical proposition: stylish prescription glasses for ninety-five dollars, sold directly to consumers online. They cut out the middleman, just as Luxottica had done decades earlier, but this time against the giant itself. ... The public response was immediate and powerful. Customers flocked to the new brand, and Warby Parker's valuation soared past one billion dollars. Luxottica's stock, which had been climbing for decades, suddenly wavered. The headlines shifted. Analysts began to question whether the empire was finally vulnerable. But even this disruption had limits. Warby Parker, for all its success, captured only a small fraction of the market. The giant was wounded, not defeated. And the price of your glasses barely budged.

11
00:08:17,615 --> 00:09:03,816
The story of Luxottica is not a tale of villains and heroes. It is a masterclass in the mechanics of modern monopoly. Leonardo Del Vecchio did not break the law. He simply understood something that most business leaders miss: that the most profitable monopoly is not the one that eliminates all competitors, but the one that creates the illusion of competition. ... When you walk into a store and see dozens of brands, you feel the comfort of choice. But if all those brands share the same parent company, the same supply chain, the same pricing strategy, and the same insurance network, then your choice is an illusion. The empire grew not by selling better products, but by controlling every path to purchase until all roads led back to Agordo.

12
00:09:03,816 --> 00:09:35,639
The collapse was not caused by one mistake. It was a series of decisions. Decisions hidden in the shadows. And that is where the real story begins. ... If you found this investigation valuable, please support the channel by subscribing and leaving a comment. Share this episode with someone who buys expensive glasses. Let them know the truth behind the price tag. Subscribe to Shadow Empires for more hidden histories of corporate power, and may God bless you.

